description: {"blocks":[{"key":"79gqr","text":"This protocol was created to be read in conjunction with the publication about the manual annotation of the terpene synthase (TPS) gene family in Melaleuca alternifolia (tea tree). It provides additional information regarding the computational methods mentioned in the manuscript, especially concerning specific commands for reproducibility of the methodology. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"italic","offset":126,"length":3},{"style":"italic","offset":146,"length":23}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"4oc21","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"9d99r","text":"When using and citing this protocol, please also refer to the original article publication as mentioned in the metadata section of this protocol.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
keywords: Melaleuca alternifolia, terpenoids, TPS annotation, Myrtaceae, tea tree
manuscript_citation: The terpene synthase genes of Melaleuca alternifolia (tea tree) and comparative gene family analysis among Myrtaceae essential oil crops

status.info: We use this protocol and it's working

steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"eg8ev","text":"The genome of the tea tree reference genotype SCU01 (BioProject PRJNA702189) was used for the manual TPS annotation. Genes in the tea tree genome sequence were automatically predicted with Fgenesh++ v7.2.2 (RRID:SCR_018928) and GenemarkET+ v4.59 (RRID:SCR_011930). The methods for the Fgenesh++ prediction are explained in Voelker et al. (2021) and the accompanying protocol.For the Genemark prediction, the same NCBI nr-protein plant database and RNA-seq reads were used as evidence. The protein database was aligned to the genome assembly using ProtHint v2.5.0 (RRID:SCR_021167) and RNAseq spliced read alignments were created with STAR v2.7 (RRID:SCR_004463):","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":64,"length":11},{"key":1,"offset":323,"length":21},{"key":2,"offset":366,"length":8}],"data":{}},{"key":"98gre","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"6mgp3","text":"- Julia Voelker, Mervyn Shepherd, Ramil Mauleon, A high-quality draft genome for Melaleuca alternifolia (tea tree): a new platform for evolutionary genomics of myrtaceous terpene-rich species, Gigabyte, 2021  https://doi.org/10.46471/gigabyte.28","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"sub","offset":0,"length":245},{"style":"italic","offset":193,"length":8}],"entityRanges":[{"key":3,"offset":208,"length":37}],"data":{}},{"key":"318lg","text":"- Julia Voelker 2021. {"blocks":[{"key":"c0k4a","text":"A phylogenetic trees was created for the predicted M. alternifolia TPS protein sequences. {"blocks":[{"key":"ebqko","text":"Exonerate alignment of TPS sequences","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":36}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"770mq","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"bb0a8","text":"As further evidence for exon-intron borders, TPS protein sequences were aligned to the genome assembly with Exonerate v2.4.0 (RRID:SCR_016088). First, protein sequences matching the ‘terpene synthase’ keyword search were retrieved from Phytozome v13 (accessed 20/05/2021) for A. thaliana ARAPORT11, C. citriodora v2.1, E. grandis v2.0, P. trichocarpa v4.1 and V. vinifera v2.1. These sequences were then aligned to the genome using the protein2genome mode of Exonerate. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"italic","offset":276,"length":11},{"style":"italic","offset":299,"length":13},{"style":"italic","offset":319,"length":10},{"style":"italic","offset":336,"length":14},{"style":"italic","offset":360,"length":11}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"ckb25","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"ak58","text":" ","type":"atomic","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":0,"length":1}],"data":{}},{"key":"c6oio","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{"0":{"type":"code_insert","mutability":"IMMUTABLE","data":{"blocks":[{"data":{},"depth":0,"entityRanges":[],"inlineStyleRanges":[],"key":"f7hjo","text":"#Align reference sequences of TPS proteins to genome","type":"unstyled"},{"data":{},"depth":0,"entityRanges":[],"inlineStyleRanges":[],"key":"5pv9a","text":"exonerate -m protein2genome -t /path/to/assembly.fasta -q /path/to/terpene_synthase_ref_protein_phytozome.fa --querytype protein --targettype dna -V 1 --showalignment FALSE --showvulgar TRUE --showtargetgff TRUE --fsmmemory 500 --percent 40 --dpmemory 50 --maxintron 5000 \u003e protein2genome_TPS.out","type":"unstyled"},{"data":{},"depth":0,"entityRanges":[],"inlineStyleRanges":[],"key":"eerhj","text":"","type":"unstyled"},{"data":{},"depth":0,"entityRanges":[],"inlineStyleRanges":[],"key":"ba9j6","text":"#Filter output for visualisation in genome viewer","type":"unstyled"},{"data":{},"depth":0,"entityRanges":[],"inlineStyleRanges":[],"key":"6ddah","text":"grep -v 'vulgar' protein2genome_TPS.out | sed '1d; {"blocks":[{"key":"n2bs","text":"RNAseq read trimming","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":20}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"42lkl","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"3jou0","text":"M. alternifolia RNAseq data from three other individual trees of the same chemotype (BioProject PRJNA388506; SRR5630605, SRR5630611, SRR5630622) were downloaded and converted to fastq format with the NCBI SRA toolkit. Quality controls were undertaken with FastQC (RRID:SCR_014583) and reads were trimmed with Flexbar (RRID:SCR_013001).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"italic","offset":0,"length":15}],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":96,"length":11}],"data":{}},{"key":"7fgnm","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"1r0ui","text":" ","type":"atomic","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":1,"offset":0,"length":1}],"data":{}},{"key":"e7mj4","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{"0":{"type":"link","mutability":"MUTABLE","data":{"guid":"30B2C218943011ECABAA0A58A9FEAC02","url":"https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/bioproject/388506"}},"1":{"type":"code_insert","mutability":"IMMUTABLE","data":{"blocks":[{"data":{},"depth":0,"entityRanges":[],"inlineStyleRanges":[],"key":"9nr1v","text":"#Identify adapter sequences in each read library","type":"unstyled"},{"data":{},"depth":0,"entityRanges":[],"inlineStyleRanges":[],"key":"88gib","text":"bbmap/bbmerge.sh in1=RNAseq_1.fastq in2=RNAseq_2.fastq outa=adapters.fasta","type":"unstyled"},{"data":{},"depth":0,"entityRanges":[],"inlineStyleRanges":[],"key":"2i9pt","text":"","type":"unstyled"},{"data":{},"depth":0,"entityRanges":[],"inlineStyleRanges":[],"key":"40lrh","text":"#Trim reads and remove identified adapters","type":"unstyled"},{"data":{},"depth":0,"entityRanges":[],"inlineStyleRanges":[],"key":"6uocv","text":"flexbar -r RNAseq_1.fastq -p RNAseq_2.fastq -a adapters.fasta --adapter-trim-end RIGHT -adapter-error-rate 0.1 --adapter-min-overlap 6 -ap ON --min-read-length 40 --max-uncalled 1 -q TAIL -qf i1.8 -qt 30 -pre-trim-left 10 -t RNAseq_trim","type":"unstyled"}],"entityMap":{}}}}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"9po0j","text":"M. alternifolia tree and multi-species tree","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":43},{"style":"italic","offset":0,"length":16}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"670gp","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"css1i","text":"The M. alternifolia TPS protein sequences were manually assessed in Unipro UGENE v39.0 (RRID:SCR_005579) and where possible, trimmed to the start of the RRx8W motif. Multiple-sequence alignment (MSA) was carried out with the inbuilt MUSCLE tool (RRID:SCR_011812), and columns with gaps \u003e75% were removed from the alignment. The trimmed MSA output was converted into NEXUS format and used as input for phylogenetic tree construction using PhyML v3.3 (RRID:SCR_014629).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"italic","offset":4,"length":15}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"45qck","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"8n7ef","text":" ","type":"atomic","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":0,"length":1}],"data":{}},{"key":"4qjci","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"28uqm","text":"Similarly, the sequences for all species were loaded into Unipro UGENE and where possible, trimmed to the start of the RRx8W motif, as already done for M. alternifolia. Next, MSA was carried out for all species, using MUSCLE and trimming the resulting alignment to remove all columns with \u003e75% gap representation. Phylogenetic tree construction was carried out with 100 bootstraps and settings as already mentioned for the M. alternifolia tree. After the whole tree was visualised and annotated in iTOL v6, different clades were exported into separated trees for a clearer visualisation of each subfamily.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"italic","offset":152,"length":15},{"style":"italic","offset":423,"length":15}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{"0":{"type":"code_insert","mutability":"IMMUTABLE","data":{"blocks":[{"data":{},"depth":0,"entityRanges":[],"inlineStyleRanges":[],"key":"1a0dp","text":"#PhyML command for M. alternifolia tree","type":"unstyled"},{"data":{},"depth":0,"entityRanges":[],"inlineStyleRanges":[],"key":"ausq9","text":"mpirun -np 10 ~/programs/phyml-3.3.20200621/src/phyml-mpi -i Malternifolia_TPS_muscle.nex -b 100 -d aa -m JTT -v e -a e -o tl --print_trace --no_memory_check --leave_duplicates -c 4","type":"unstyled"}],"entityMap":{}}}}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"c5vap","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"8aaim","text":"Manual adjustment of TPS gene structures","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":40}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"3codq","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"7uimf","text":"The GFF-file containing exons and splice sites from TPS alignments were visualised in Apollo (RRID:SCR_001936) together with RNAseq read alignments, the Fgenesh++ and the GenemarkET+ gene predictions and the genome sequence. Potential terpene synthases were identified based on TPS alignments and predicted protein sequences containing TPS Pfam domains. To identify the C-terminal (PF03936) and N-terminal (PF01397) TPS Pfam domains, the GenemarkET+ and Fgenesh++ protein sequence predictions were screened for PfamA domains (RRID:SCR_004726) using InterProScan (RRID:SCR_005829) in Galaxy Europe (RRID:SCR_006281). ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":382,"length":7},{"key":1,"offset":407,"length":7},{"key":2,"offset":583,"length":13}],"data":{}},{"key":"c2q61","text":"All lines of evidence were taken into consideration for the manual annotation of the terpene synthase gene structures using the genome annotation editor Apollo. {"blocks":[{"key":"26lg7","text":"Quality control and removal of duplicates","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":41}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"en3db","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"c782e","text":"The manually annotated TPS genes were named consecutively (MaltTPS001-MaltTPS73) based on their location on a scaffold, from lowest to highest scaffold number, and their location within the scaffold. Some TPS sequences, however, seemed to be highly similar, so percent sequence identity matrixes were calculated via multiple sequence alignment in Clustal Omega v2.1 (RRID:SCR_001591) with default settings, using the predicted protein, CDS and genomic TPS sequences as input, respectively. Furthermore, the scaffolds containing TPS were aligned in all-vs-all manner using NUCmer v3.1 (RRID:SCR_018171) and Minimap2, respectively. Each scaffold was manually assessed for overlaps with other scaffolds and potential assembly errors or scaffold duplications by going through the alignment outputs and also visualising alignments with Alvis.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"italic","offset":23,"length":3},{"style":"italic","offset":205,"length":3},{"style":"italic","offset":528,"length":3}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"25trj","text":".
